<!-- MAGNOLIA -->
<section class="magnolia-section reveal">
  <div class="magnolia-inner">
    <h2>The magnolia that refused to die — and what it taught me about healing</h2>
    <p>I was raised beneath the branches of a magnolia tree in my family garden. It was my shelter, my refuge. That tall, steady guardian felt eternal.</p>
    <p>Until one day a storm brought it down.</p>
    <p>I was devastated. But every day afterwards, I watered the soil where it once stood. Adults told me it would not return. But I kept watering. Stubbornness — and perhaps faith in renewal — has always been part of me.</p>
    <p>One day, a tiny shoot emerged.</p>
    <p>Today, it greets me whenever I return home. Years later, <em>Magnolia</em> became the subject of my clinical dissertation. It reminded me that resilience is quiet. It grows beneath the surface long before anyone can see it. It asks for patience, consistency, and belief in what cannot yet be observed.</p>
    <p><em>That is what healing through plant medicine looks like.</em> It is not dramatic. It is not instant. But it is real, and it is yours — rooted in the body's own intelligence, supported by centuries of botanical tradition, and tended with care.</p>
    <p>That is the practice I am building. That is the kind of practitioner I am.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- GRADUATION -->
<section class="graduation-section reveal">
  <div class="graduation-inner">
    <h2>On the day I became a qualified practitioner</h2>
    <p>Standing in that room on graduation day, I looked around at the people beside me — practitioners from different disciplines, different backgrounds, different stories of what had brought them to this path. Every single one of us had overcome something to sit in that room.</p>
    <p>I thought about what this journey had given me beyond knowledge. Self-discovery. The moments in a clinic session, or a case study, or a conversation with a classmate, when you realise you are capable of more than you had imagined. A community of people who understand that health is an ecosystem — that none of us works in isolation, and that we will need one another.</p>
    <p>I thought about the wholeness we had been cultivating in ourselves — because that is what we offer our clients. Not just protocols and prescriptions. <strong>Presence. Listening. The courage to sit with complexity.</strong></p>
    <p>It takes courage to follow a path that is not always understood. To choose a form of medicine that asks more questions than it answers, that treats the person rather than the symptom, that works with time rather than against it.</p>
    <p>I chose it anyway. I would choose it again, every time.</p>
    <p><em>Your journey is inspirational. This one certainly was.</em></p>
  </div>
